  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He wishes the fate of Sodom (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), namely ruin, to befall that man. ולא נחם, and may He (Jahveh) not let it repent Him, is adverbially used: without feeling compunction for the destruction, i.e., without pity. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 20:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " destruction is depicted under the figure of the terrors of a town beleaguered by enemies and suddenly taken. זעקה, the wailing cry of the afflicted townspeople; תּרוּעה, the war-cry of the enemies breaking in; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 15:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
